00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:42.140
and then go into some
other things.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:45.330
And I have lots of pictures to
show, to give it a little bit

00:02:45.330 --> 00:02:46.580
of texture.

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:56.610
So Hunter Dupree talks about
what he calls the Great

00:02:56.610 --> 00:03:01.605
Instauration, which is actually

00:03:01.605 --> 00:03:04.060
was allusion to Bacon.

00:03:04.060 --> 00:03:07.020
And a few people comment on his
distinction between the

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:10.430
Baconian scientists who sort of
engaged in the affairs of

00:03:10.430 --> 00:03:12.900
the world and the more
Cartesian model of a

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:15.940
scientist, who is sort of
isolated in the laboratory in

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:18.140
a purely intellectual space, and
that's an interesting way

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:24.510
to think about this whole thing,
and how these things

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:27.370
sort of formulated in the
years leading up to the

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:29.720
Second World War.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.840
What is the generally accepted
start of the Second World War?

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:34.090
Anybody know?

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:40.210
Just date-wise?

00:03:42.290 --> 00:03:43.258
Yeah?

00:03:43.258 --> 00:03:45.680
AUDIENCE: Was it August 1939?

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:47.180
PROFESSOR: Close.

00:03:47.180 --> 00:03:49.270
Within a month, September
1939.

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:50.390
AUDIENCE: The first
day of September.

00:03:50.390 --> 00:03:55.080
PROFESSOR: What happens
in September 1939?

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:56.430
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:56.430 --> 00:03:57.030
PROFESSOR: Sorry.

00:03:57.030 --> 00:03:57.710
AUDIENCE: Nazi invasion.

00:03:57.710 --> 00:03:58.030
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:03:58.030 --> 00:03:59.610
Nazi invasion of Poland.

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:02.190
That's the sort of generally
accepted moment, although

00:04:02.190 --> 00:04:04.770
there's the Spanish Civil War
before that and what not.

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:07.619
When does the US get
into the war?

00:04:07.619 --> 00:04:09.010
AUDIENCE: December 7, 1941.

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:13.560
PROFESSOR: December 7, 1941,
Pearl Harbor, more than two

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:15.970
years later.

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:20.529
A very long period, where Europe
and most of Asia is at

00:04:20.529 --> 00:04:23.800
war and the US is not only not
as the war-- it's not like

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:26.000
when we get into it, there are
a lot of people who really

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.805
don't want us too and think we
should stay out, Charles

00:04:28.805 --> 00:04:32.090
Lindbergh among them.

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:35.340
And so this is this kind
of limbo period where--

00:04:38.730 --> 00:04:40.720
and it's actually in a
way the same as in

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:41.830
the first world war.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:44.030
The US is very late getting into
it and has a lot of time

00:04:44.030 --> 00:04:45.280
to prepare.

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:50.920
If the US had gotten into the
war in September 1939, we

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:53.180
would have been a
lot of trouble.

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:54.470
There was nothing.

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:57.410
There was no military to
speak of in a sense.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:01.120
Whereas by December 1941,
things had been

00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:02.800
gearing up for a while.

00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:06.810
And that's this period where
not only does Bush get

00:05:06.810 --> 00:05:10.770
interested and involved, but
also the predecessor is--

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:12.720
there's this very interesting,
sort of curious committee

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:16.010
called the Scientific Aids to
Learning, that is done under

00:05:16.010 --> 00:05:18.690
the National Academy of
Sciences, which includes

00:05:18.690 --> 00:05:21.810
Vannevar Bush, James Bryant
Conant, who's is the president

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:24.620
of Harvard, a chemist, and also
Frank Jewett, who we've

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:27.930
mentioned before, who
is an MIT graduate.

00:05:27.930 --> 00:05:29.840
He taught here.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:35.070
He is then head of Bell Labs,
head of research for AT&amp;T, and

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:37.350
actually president of the
National Academy of Sciences

00:05:37.350 --> 00:05:39.910
in the 1930s.

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:41.920
And these guys all get together
on this sort of

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:44.310
abstract study about--

00:05:44.310 --> 00:05:45.480
anybody know what
that refers to,

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.600
Scientific Aids to Learning?

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:52.260
It's a very modern
topic in a way.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:55.210
How can we use new technology
to help education?

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:57.160
What are the new technologies
they're talking about?

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:04.000
LP records, 33 and
1/3 records--

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
does anybody know what
a record is?

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:13.450
LP records, 16 millimeter
film, to some degree 35

00:06:13.450 --> 00:06:16.390
millimeter photography, these
are all the cutting edge media

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:18.400
technologies in 1939.

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:21.490
And there are people saying,
gee, there must be way to

00:06:21.490 --> 00:06:23.640
improve education using
these things.

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:25.510
And it's interesting when
you think about--

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:26.950
we may have mentioned
this before.

00:06:26.950 --> 00:06:28.290
We'll certainly mention
it later--

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:31.230
Vannevar Bush's great paper,
"As We May Think," where he

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:33.780
introduces this idea of the
memex, which is very much

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:36.760
credited as being a kind of
predecessor to the World Wide

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:39.150
Web, so right about
this time period.

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:42.180
So he's got exposure to these
sort of media film

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:43.690
technologies at the time.

00:06:43.690 --> 00:06:45.950
And in the course of that
committee, these guys get

00:06:45.950 --> 00:06:47.520
together and they think there's

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:48.990
really something happening.

00:06:48.990 --> 00:06:51.940
The United States is generally
mobilizing.

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:54.390
Even though there's a lot of
political debate, people

00:06:54.390 --> 00:06:58.210
really see that the US needs
to build up the military

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:00.110
during this period.

00:07:00.110 --> 00:07:04.340
And it's not at all clear that
the scientific talent of the

00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:06.870
country is going to be utilized
in the best way.

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:08.720
And a lot of people, and we
talked about this, during

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:11.600
World War I felt that it really
wasn't utilized in the

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.790
most effective way.

00:07:13.790 --> 00:07:18.420
And Dupree talks about, there's
a lot of different

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:23.030
options for ways that you might
bring either scientists,

00:07:23.030 --> 00:07:26.400
to use that term generally, or
people like you, to bear on

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:27.030
the war effort.

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:28.310
What might those ways be?

00:07:28.310 --> 00:07:30.000
What are the different options
you might have?

00:07:39.540 --> 00:07:42.170
Well, one option is to just
draft you all, send you into

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:45.270
the military, and then I've got
lots of smart MIT people

00:07:45.270 --> 00:07:48.050
working in the army.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:50.460
Especially the army in 1940,
you'd probably spent a lot of

00:07:50.460 --> 00:07:52.270
time peeling potatoes.

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:54.370
You'd probably get handed a
rifle and told to run into the

00:07:54.370 --> 00:07:55.640
machine gun fire.

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:57.790
I'm going to draft you and
rather than you being sent to

00:07:57.790 --> 00:08:05.940
the front, I'm going to send
to the Watertown Arsenal to

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:09.830
make guns or to help engineer
the manufacture of guns.

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:11.660
OK, you go work for the
government, you work in a

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:15.700
government facility, and you
help with some important job.

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:18.160
That's not a bad way
to do it actually.

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:22.130
But you end up working
on things

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:24.230
that are already existing.

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:28.200
And so there are labs internal
to the government.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:29.020
The Navy has them.

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:31.180
The Army has them.

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:33.409
Even the Army Air Force had
some stuff like that.

00:08:37.380 --> 00:08:41.820
But they were generally seen as
not the most cutting edge.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:43.620
And there's a lot of truth
to be said to that.

00:08:43.620 --> 00:08:46.770
They were sort of concerned
with building weapons that

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:50.240
they had built for a long time,
not really very good at

00:08:50.240 --> 00:08:53.100
dealing with things like
electronics or other new

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:55.880
things, and very, very hard for
them to think about stuff

00:08:55.880 --> 00:08:57.260
that was outside the box.

00:08:57.260 --> 00:09:00.900
If you were in the Navy, the
Navy had a great cadre of

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:03.480
people who knew how to build
warships because they built

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:05.490
best warships and that's
all they did.

00:09:05.490 --> 00:09:07.510
But outside of building
warships, it was very hard to

00:09:07.510 --> 00:09:08.780
think about what you might do.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:11.170
Because that's what the Navy
did, was they built warships,

00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:13.290
to some degree airplanes,
mostly warships and

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:14.940
submarines.

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:16.780
You could send all the
scientists and engineers into

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:19.700
industrial labs and have them
work in industry and close

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:20.950
down the school.

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:26.920
You could organize a separate
corps, where you say--

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:28.800
actually there are some things
like this today.

00:09:28.800 --> 00:09:31.270
There's the Public
Health Service.

00:09:31.270 --> 00:09:35.360
There's the NOAH corps, which
is the oceanographic corp.

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:38.330
These are sort of little
quasi-military organizations

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:40.470
that are peppered around
the government.

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:42.420
You could say let's have
a government--

00:09:42.420 --> 00:09:43.850
well, there's a Peace Corps.

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.180
I'm sure you've heard of that.

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:48.730
You could have the War Corps.

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:51.630
And a lot of different options
there for organizing.

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:53.460
And these guys started to
become worried that they

00:09:53.460 --> 00:09:56.720
didn't think that left to its
own devices, it was going to

00:09:56.720 --> 00:09:58.150
go the right way.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:02.320
And so Bush and his group,
particularly Bush in using his

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:05.530
political connections, gets them
took to create this thing

00:10:05.530 --> 00:10:08.580
called the National Defense
Research Committee.

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:12.440
And he writes this famous memo
that Dupree talks about, in

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:15.930
June of 1940, which
happens to be--

00:10:15.930 --> 00:10:19.530
anybody know that picture is?

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:23.988
What happens in June 1940?

00:10:23.988 --> 00:10:25.470
AUDIENCE: Germans take France.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:26.000
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:29.070
France falls to the Nazis.

00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:31.480
So this is what, about
less than a year

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:33.000
after the war starts.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.270
And here you have Hitler
walking down--

00:10:35.270 --> 00:10:39.770
there's Hitler right there,
Albert Speer, by the way,

00:10:39.770 --> 00:10:42.300
right there, touring Paris.

00:10:42.300 --> 00:10:46.990
And that's a pretty shocking
image for the West to see.

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:55.240
And it was a time of
doom and gloom.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:59.112
A time of really the sense that
if the US didn't get off

00:10:59.112 --> 00:11:02.990
its rear end and start doing
things, bad things

00:11:02.990 --> 00:11:04.220
were going to happen.

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:06.420
And you also have the
Battle of Britain.

00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:09.960
And the Battle of Britain
refers, of course, the Nazi--

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:12.380
they were next going
to invade England.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:15.120
But Hitler wouldn't do it until
Goering could give him

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:16.520
air superiority.

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:18.690
And so they started going
over and bombing and

00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:20.050
preparing the ground.

00:11:20.050 --> 00:11:22.420
And they never quite got air
superiority, because of the

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:25.210
Spitfires and the Hurricanes and
all this, not least of it

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:26.500
aided by radar.

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:30.440
And so in the spring of 1940,
into the summer of 1940, is

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:33.000
what they call the
Blitz in London.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.140
I'm sure if you've
been to London,

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:36.170
you've seen that stuff.

00:11:36.170 --> 00:11:39.100
Not only is there this sense
of military emergency, but

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:41.390
there's this sense that
a lot of the danger is

00:11:41.390 --> 00:11:42.770
coming from the sky.

00:11:42.770 --> 00:11:45.090
And we really don't know how to
shoot down airplanes and we

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:46.570
don't know how to combat
airplanes.

00:11:46.570 --> 00:11:49.080
And there's this sense
of defense that is

00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:50.330
not being taken up.

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:55.640
And so these guys from the
Scientific Aids to Learning,

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:58.160
and this memo that Bush writes,
particularly concerned

00:11:58.160 --> 00:12:02.460
about anti-aircraft defenses--

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:11.550
and Harry Hopkins, who is the
chief of staff for the

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:14.270
president, basically puts this
memo in front of him.

00:12:14.270 --> 00:12:18.410
And he writes across
it, OK, FDR.

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:19.890
And that's the letter.

00:12:19.890 --> 00:12:22.470
And with that letter, in the
government world, if you have

00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:25.360
that signature on your letter
you can pretty much do

00:12:25.360 --> 00:12:26.060
anything you want.

00:12:26.060 --> 00:12:28.140
It's literally like
a blank check.

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:31.970
And Bush goes around in the
summer of 1940 collecting all

00:12:31.970 --> 00:12:35.520
these people to work
in this National

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:39.000
Defense Research Committee.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.280
And they divided
up initially--

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:44.950
it's later called the OSRD.

00:12:44.950 --> 00:12:46.570
And it's a little bit confusing
the way the

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:47.820
terminology works.

00:12:52.590 --> 00:12:55.060
But they divided up into
different divisions.

00:12:55.060 --> 00:12:57.630
There's a division for transport
and communication;

00:12:57.630 --> 00:13:01.140
aircraft, submarines, and mine
defense; guns, projectiles,

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:04.940
and armor; and bombs, fuels,
gases, and chemistry.

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.540
And these tend to be things that
are not things that they

00:13:07.540 --> 00:13:09.380
feel are being addressed

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:11.550
adequately through the services.

00:13:11.550 --> 00:13:14.540
What's the one thing they
leave out, by the way?

00:13:14.540 --> 00:13:16.180
They don't go near, they
don't touch it?

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:21.410
Aviation.

00:13:21.410 --> 00:13:24.280
They feel that the NACA, which
Bush has then been chair of,

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:27.680
the predecessor to NASA
has aviation sewed up.

00:13:27.680 --> 00:13:29.260
AUDIENCE: Is fire control
listed there?

00:13:29.260 --> 00:13:31.430
PROFESSOR: Fire control is
under guns, projectiles,

00:13:31.430 --> 00:13:34.670
armor, and materials.

00:13:34.670 --> 00:13:39.660
And so what they do in a sense
is they grab onto all of the

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:45.060
technologies that don't fit
neatly into the services, the

00:13:45.060 --> 00:13:46.340
military services.

00:13:46.340 --> 00:13:49.420
And you'll see this again when
we talk about DARPA.

00:13:49.420 --> 00:13:51.990
Because the Navy knows
how to build ships.

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:54.040
They're not going tell the
Navy how to build ships.

00:13:54.040 --> 00:13:56.170
But the Navy doesn't know the
first thing about radar, and

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:58.730
they're not particularly good
at radio, and they certainly

00:13:58.730 --> 00:14:03.320
don't think very much about
other sorts of things.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:04.310
There's this great quote.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:06.700
I don't know if it's in that
reading, from Bush, where he

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:09.740
says, there were those who
protested that the action of

00:14:09.740 --> 00:14:12.750
setting up the NDRC
was an end run.

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:15.080
A grab by which a small company
of scientists and

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:19.160
engineers, acting outside
established channels, got hold

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:21.240
of the authority and money
for the program of

00:14:21.240 --> 00:14:23.340
developing new weapons.

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:25.920
So they met a lot of resistance,
particularly from

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:28.980
the military itself, saying why
are you guys doing this?

00:14:28.980 --> 00:14:32.170
And Bush says, that's in fact
exactly what it was.

00:14:32.170 --> 00:14:33.030
It was an end run.

00:14:33.030 --> 00:14:34.940
They went around all the
established people.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:37.750
There are millions and millions
of dollars flowing

00:14:37.750 --> 00:14:40.590
into Navy laboratories, flowing
into other things, but

00:14:40.590 --> 00:14:43.140
building very traditional
weapons and things along the

00:14:43.140 --> 00:14:45.860
lines that they didn't feel
were going to be really

00:14:45.860 --> 00:14:48.210
thinking differently.

00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:49.570
So they set this thing up.

00:14:49.570 --> 00:14:51.730
It's outside the Army.

00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:53.780
It's outside the Navy.

00:14:53.780 --> 00:14:57.350
And you have no idea what a
bureaucracy is like until you

00:14:57.350 --> 00:15:00.640
look at the Army or
the Navy in 1940.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:03.230
These are organizations that
have existed for hundreds of

00:15:03.230 --> 00:15:06.690
years practically, or at least
150 years at that point.

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:12.410
There was not a lot of rapid
change going on, except maybe

00:15:12.410 --> 00:15:15.940
in the air arm in the Army.

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:21.350
And they bring these people on
who can actually understand,

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:25.900
who can manage the research and
pretty much write checks

00:15:25.900 --> 00:15:28.030
with government money,
with a handshake.

00:15:28.030 --> 00:15:31.230
This is not the NSF, where you
have to go through peer review

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:33.230
and you have to get your program
approved and all the

00:15:33.230 --> 00:15:35.070
sort of things that a
lot of people here

00:15:35.070 --> 00:15:36.370
on campus do today.

00:15:36.370 --> 00:15:40.680
This is like, show up at
somebody's lab, ask them if

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:41.750
they'd like to be involved?

00:15:41.750 --> 00:15:45.330
And the next thing they know,
they got a check for $250,000,

00:15:45.330 --> 00:15:47.735
which in 1940 is a lot of
money for scientist.

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:53.940
And one of the things they
really get right early on is

00:15:53.940 --> 00:15:56.720
this whole business about
electronics and what role

00:15:56.720 --> 00:16:00.930
electronics could potentially
play in the war effort.

00:16:00.930 --> 00:16:02.280
There's radar.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:03.470
There's computing.

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:05.980
There's different kinds of
systems integration.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:08.080
I'll talk more and I'll show
you some pictures about

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:10.880
proximity fuses and
fire control and

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:12.410
I'll mention radar.

00:16:12.410 --> 00:16:14.940
And also of course, and Dupree
mentions this, there's this

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:15.920
uranium committee.

00:16:15.920 --> 00:16:18.350
Which is another one of these
things that gee, it seems like

00:16:18.350 --> 00:16:19.270
it has potential.

00:16:19.270 --> 00:16:22.210
It's a bunch of pointy-headed
scientists telling us some

00:16:22.210 --> 00:16:24.700
abstract thing that could be
the greatest ever, but

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:25.980
what do they know?

00:16:25.980 --> 00:16:29.350
These are like Hungarian
physicists, who just have this

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:31.520
idea on a blackboard.

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:34.360
And this uranium committee
had sort of existed.

00:16:34.360 --> 00:16:35.820
But the Army didn't
really own it.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:37.180
The Navy didn't really own it.

00:16:37.180 --> 00:16:42.700
And of course it belongs then,
it gets folded into the NDRC.

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:45.060
What does it become?

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:45.560
AUDIENCE: The Manhattan
Project.

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:47.730
PROFESSOR: The Manhattan
Project.

00:16:47.730 --> 00:16:50.600
Then it actually branches
out of NDRC.

00:16:50.600 --> 00:16:53.540
For a grant from the NSF.

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:57.170
And say I want to get $100,000,
how much do I need

00:16:57.170 --> 00:17:00.000
to get from the NSF?

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:01.710
Anybody know what the
overhead rate is?

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:11.930
It's like-- and I'll get this
within 5% because I don't

00:17:11.930 --> 00:17:14.560
follow it every year-- it's
like 63 and 1/2%.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:17.040
So if I want to get a grant,
any faculty member you work

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:20.280
with that goes to the NSF and
needs $100,000 to do the work,

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:23.359
I have to get $163,500.

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:26.599
And that $63,500 from the top,
just goes right off the top

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:29.260
into MIT's bank account.

00:17:29.260 --> 00:17:31.743
And the reason I ask if you've
heard about it, because a lot

00:17:31.743 --> 00:17:33.470
of faculty complain about
it a lot because it

00:17:33.470 --> 00:17:35.050
feels kind of painful.

00:17:35.050 --> 00:17:37.200
And what does it do?

00:17:37.200 --> 00:17:39.830
Theoretically, it goes to pay
for keeping the lights, on

00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:43.600
keeping the heat on, somebody
to come in and sweep the lab

00:17:43.600 --> 00:17:46.500
out at night, all the different
things, the

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:49.610
paperwork, that it takes to
actually run these grants.

00:17:49.610 --> 00:17:52.280
And it is expensive
to do that.

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:55.260
And most faculty see it as a
big burden because gee, my

00:17:55.260 --> 00:18:00.560
$63,500 which the NSF gave me,
suddenly gets taken as rent by

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:02.480
my landlord.

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:03.780
And what do I get in return?

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:05.970
All I do is get somebody who
comes in to sweep the floor

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:09.100
and it sounds like
a lot of money.

00:18:09.100 --> 00:18:11.770
And Dupree really tells you
why that was so important.

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:15.670
And it was invented in this
month, pretty much.

00:18:15.670 --> 00:18:18.710
And it was one of the most
critical ideas of getting all

00:18:18.710 --> 00:18:21.540
this stuff to work so
impressively, which was--

00:18:24.580 --> 00:18:29.070
MIT's total research budget in
1940, before this started, was

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:33.340
on the order of $300,000, the
entire research budget for the

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:36.230
entire Institute.

00:18:36.230 --> 00:18:37.535
I wrote the number down here.

00:18:43.460 --> 00:19:01.550
Well, in total MIT got from
the NDRC, $116 million.

00:19:04.870 --> 00:19:09.340
$116 million, even in today's
world, is a lot of research.

00:19:09.340 --> 00:19:10.070
And what does that mean?

00:19:10.070 --> 00:19:12.400
It mostly means people and desks
and laboratories and all

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:13.530
that stuff.

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:18.050
If MIT had to pay for building
all those buildings and

00:19:18.050 --> 00:19:20.730
building all those desks and
building all that heating and

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:23.620
all that infrastructure, it have
bankrupted the Institute

00:19:23.620 --> 00:19:26.630
by the time it got
to $3 million.

00:19:26.630 --> 00:19:32.250
But they added this overhead
charge on there so that any

00:19:32.250 --> 00:19:36.810
time money came for research to
hire post-docs or research

00:19:36.810 --> 00:19:40.160
assistants or technicians or
other people, it came with

00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:41.120
this overhead.

00:19:41.120 --> 00:19:46.160
That meant that the dollar
figure could grow infinitely

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:48.970
large, infinitely large.

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:53.320
And again, think about that
$300,000 to $116 million in

00:19:53.320 --> 00:19:55.040
under five years.

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:58.690
We wish we saw that kind
of growth now.

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:01.360
And it was only able to happen
because they built into this

00:20:01.360 --> 00:20:04.380
idea of the research contract,
this notion of indirect costs.

00:20:04.380 --> 00:20:06.040
It was really a very fundamental
thing that we

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:07.390
still live with today.

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:09.940
That means that if I as a
faculty member went to DARPA

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:13.340
and I got $100 million
contract, MIT

00:20:13.340 --> 00:20:14.100
could support it.

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:16.510
And they might have to build me
a building, which happens

00:20:16.510 --> 00:20:18.700
all the time, you see these
buildings around here.

00:20:18.700 --> 00:20:20.240
But they could actually do it.

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:29.770
The other thing about it was all
of the research contracts,

00:20:29.770 --> 00:20:32.100
the military, the only thing
they knew how to do up until

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:33.625
then was to buy stuff.

00:20:33.625 --> 00:20:34.560
It's called procurement.

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:36.910
It's still something
they do a lot of.

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:39.450
So if I wanted to do an
experimental radar set, the

00:20:39.450 --> 00:20:42.080
only way I had to do it was to
come to MIT and go, we'd like

00:20:42.080 --> 00:20:44.030
to buy 10 radar sets.

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:45.960
And we probably won't even use
them and they may not even

00:20:45.960 --> 00:20:47.970
work, but at least we'll have
a contract that has a

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:49.460
procurement.

00:20:49.460 --> 00:20:52.280
And what they invented during
this period also with this R&amp;D

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:56.380
contract, where MIT doesn't
deliver anything other than

00:20:56.380 --> 00:20:59.240
promising to put out its best
effort to do the research and

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:01.850
hopefully publish some
papers on it.

00:21:01.850 --> 00:21:03.700
That was also a pretty
revolutionary

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:04.780
idea in that point.

00:21:04.780 --> 00:21:06.330
Until that point, there
was no way for the

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:07.580
government to do that.

00:21:10.810 --> 00:21:15.520
So here's what Dupree
says about it.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:18.240
It's a nice little sentence
that captures it all.

00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:20.910
The contract was the device
by which universities and

00:21:20.910 --> 00:21:24.550
industrial research labs were
preserved as institutions,

00:21:24.550 --> 00:21:27.840
even while their social role
was radically changed.

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:29.985
I mean this was very much the
vision that people like Bush

00:21:29.985 --> 00:21:33.330
and Conant had, was we want to
keep MIT for what it is, keep

00:21:33.330 --> 00:21:35.400
it as the character
that it has.

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:38.300
Obviously, it changed during
the war in some basic ways.

00:21:38.300 --> 00:21:41.640
But it didn't change permanently
in some sense.

00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:43.650
Where there's a free flow
of ideas, there's an

00:21:43.650 --> 00:21:46.390
open flow of ideas.

00:21:46.390 --> 00:21:50.510
But I haven't addressed all
these other kinds of problems.

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:54.070
Without becoming part of the
Army, or without it becoming

00:21:54.070 --> 00:21:56.940
part of the Navy, or having
just everybody drafted and

00:21:56.940 --> 00:21:58.250
closing the place down
for five years.

00:22:01.970 --> 00:22:08.720
So the NDRC is created
in June of 1940.

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:09.780
It gets up and running.

00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:14.830
It starts to issue its first
contracts in September,

00:22:14.830 --> 00:22:16.970
October of 1940.

00:22:16.970 --> 00:22:19.040
I'll talk about the radiation
lab in a couple minutes when I

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:19.990
show the slides.

00:22:19.990 --> 00:22:23.160
Well, it's worth knowing that
they get started under the

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:27.270
NDRC in October, I
believe, of 1940.

00:22:27.270 --> 00:22:30.160
They deliver their first
radar set in March of

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:31.000
the following year.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:34.420
So think about the turnaround
there, to take a completely

00:22:34.420 --> 00:22:37.650
new technology and to deliver
something the military can use

00:22:37.650 --> 00:22:40.300
in the field in four months.

00:22:40.300 --> 00:22:42.480
It was a pretty remarkable
turn-around.

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:44.650
And in fact, some people in
their response papers

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:48.060
mentioned the intensity of the
environment that sort of

00:22:48.060 --> 00:22:50.380
developed around here
during that period.

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:59.650
And commenting, a couple people,
that it was hard to

00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:02.370
imagine it was any more intense
than it is today.

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:04.970
Although it probably was.

00:23:04.970 --> 00:23:07.230
And one thing that wasn't
really captured in the

00:23:07.230 --> 00:23:11.850
readings is why it
was so intense?

00:23:11.850 --> 00:23:16.060
What was it that was driving
people to work such long hours

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:17.940
and put such incredible
time in?

00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:20.270
Again, most of the people doing
this work are people

00:23:20.270 --> 00:23:20.890
just like you.

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:24.870
They're either students or just
recent graduates who are

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:26.120
occupying these labs.

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:36.320
Especially for the men, what
happens to all your friends?

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:38.120
AUDIENCE: Going and
getting drafted.

00:23:38.120 --> 00:23:41.350
PROFESSOR: Well, what are
all your friends doing?

00:23:41.350 --> 00:23:42.180
AUDIENCE: Getting drafted.

00:23:42.180 --> 00:23:43.915
PROFESSOR: Either getting
drafted or signing up.

00:23:46.930 --> 00:23:49.310
It's not that the people who
are working in the labs are

00:23:49.310 --> 00:23:51.420
trying to avoid getting
drafted.

00:23:51.420 --> 00:23:54.870
That's more of a product
of later wars.

00:23:54.870 --> 00:23:57.420
They're exempted from the draft
because they're doing

00:23:57.420 --> 00:23:58.920
critical work.

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:02.410
And there's a lot of social
pressure about not shirking

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:03.960
your service.

00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:07.370
So it can be seen as a kind of
embarrassment to be exempted

00:24:07.370 --> 00:24:10.650
from the draft to do
laboratory work.

00:24:10.650 --> 00:24:11.815
It's a sort of cushy
assignment.

00:24:11.815 --> 00:24:15.200
It's the sort of thing that
people like Dick Cheney and

00:24:15.200 --> 00:24:18.370
George Bush were criticized
for during

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:20.920
presidential campaigns.

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:23.080
All your friends are going off
to war and you're staying home

00:24:23.080 --> 00:24:26.770
in Cambridge, working at MIT.

00:24:26.770 --> 00:24:29.500
A lot of I think the motivation
for people was they

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:31.810
really wanted to prove they were
doing something important

00:24:31.810 --> 00:24:34.880
and making a contribution to
the war effort and not just

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:36.150
avoiding the draft.

00:24:36.150 --> 00:24:39.230
Because they were exempted
from the draft.

00:24:39.230 --> 00:24:43.850
And that they really were
serving their country in the

00:24:43.850 --> 00:24:44.940
same kind of way.

00:24:44.940 --> 00:24:47.500
This was not the Vietnam War,
which was very contentious

00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:49.260
about who went and who
didn't go and who

00:24:49.260 --> 00:24:50.210
wanted to get drafted.

00:24:50.210 --> 00:24:53.160
This was where the entire
country literally mobilized.

00:24:53.160 --> 00:24:56.430
And everybody's job, everybody's
home life,

00:24:56.430 --> 00:24:57.530
everybody moved around.

00:24:57.530 --> 00:24:58.770
And it really fundamentally
changed the

00:24:58.770 --> 00:25:00.160
country for that period.

00:25:00.160 --> 00:25:03.830
So you have this environment
inside the laboratories which

00:25:03.830 --> 00:25:05.080
is very different.

00:25:07.090 --> 00:25:11.170
So a couple of statistics, as I
mentioned MIT was the single

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:14.790
largest recipient of OSRD
already funds, I think by a

00:25:14.790 --> 00:25:19.200
factor of two or three, $116
million over five years.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:23.210
Again, that's a lot of money in
today's world, much less in

00:25:23.210 --> 00:25:25.450
1940 dollars, where the
total budget was

00:25:25.450 --> 00:25:29.250
$300,000 before then.

00:25:29.250 --> 00:25:33.120
There were about 2,300 contracts
overall in the OSRD,

00:25:33.120 --> 00:25:34.750
totaling $500 million.

00:25:34.750 --> 00:25:38.850
So MIT got more than 20%
of the total funds.

00:25:38.850 --> 00:25:42.700
It was a bit of an inside
job, no doubt about it.

00:25:42.700 --> 00:25:46.110
The Radiation Laboratory by
1942, again it was only

00:25:46.110 --> 00:25:50.180
founded in the end of 1940, so
within a year it was as large

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:53.410
as the rest of MIT
all together.

00:25:53.410 --> 00:25:55.390
And it was of course,
right there.

00:25:59.330 --> 00:26:02.930
The overhead started
out as 30% and got

00:26:02.930 --> 00:26:04.410
reduced down to 10%--

00:26:04.410 --> 00:26:06.470
again today it's 63 and 1/2%--

00:26:06.470 --> 00:26:09.670
because they didn't want to be
seen as raking off all this

00:26:09.670 --> 00:26:10.920
cash that came in.

00:26:18.990 --> 00:26:20.580
And again, there was a
lot of resistance.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:22.870
There's a great quote by Harold
Bowen, who was the head

00:26:22.870 --> 00:26:24.120
of the Naval Research
Laboratory.

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:24.980
He was an MIT graduate.

00:26:24.980 --> 00:26:26.540
He said--

00:26:26.540 --> 00:26:28.800
he's coming from within
the Navy--

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:31.160
those of us who had been working
in applied science for

00:26:31.160 --> 00:26:35.090
years cannot be blamed for not
always enthusiastically

00:26:35.090 --> 00:26:37.800
endorsing all the efforts of
the Johnny-come-latelys who

00:26:37.800 --> 00:26:39.540
inevitably steam into
Washington at the

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:40.830
beginning of the war.

00:26:40.830 --> 00:26:42.710
So that was how they viewed
Vannevar Bush and all these

00:26:42.710 --> 00:26:44.450
scientists, was they
were coming in.

00:26:44.450 --> 00:26:45.750
We've been working on radar.

00:26:45.750 --> 00:26:46.360
In fact, they did.

00:26:46.360 --> 00:26:49.750
The Naval Research Lab really
invented radar.

00:26:49.750 --> 00:26:52.000
And here comes Vannevar Bush,
saying we're going to do it

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:53.280
all at MIT.

00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:55.410
And in a certain way, taking
it away from the Naval

00:26:55.410 --> 00:26:56.200
Research Lab.

00:26:56.200 --> 00:27:00.930
Very contentious stuff, lots
of power politics going on.

