students might be like.

00:39:37.560 --> 00:39:39.520
If you ever take apart a
microwave oven, you'll see one

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:42.200
of these things inside there.

00:39:42.200 --> 00:39:43.310
In fact, that's kind
of the only place

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:44.650
you'll still find them.

00:39:44.650 --> 00:39:48.910
So this device is only
about this big.

00:39:48.910 --> 00:39:50.330
If you go to the museum,
you'll see it.

00:39:50.330 --> 00:39:52.070
It's one of the 150 objects.

00:39:52.070 --> 00:39:57.480
And radar had been invented
in the early '30s really.

00:39:57.480 --> 00:39:59.350
But it was pretty
long-wave radar.

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:01.750
I may have a picture of it.

00:40:01.750 --> 00:40:03.150
Yeah.

00:40:03.150 --> 00:40:06.590
So this is pre-World
War II radar.

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:08.500
This is built by Western
Electric, which is

00:40:08.500 --> 00:40:09.930
part of Bell Labs.

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:12.450
And there's a couple of key
things to notice about it.

00:40:12.450 --> 00:40:13.790
What do you notice about it?

00:40:17.070 --> 00:40:18.250
It's really big.

00:40:18.250 --> 00:40:19.500
Why is it big?

00:40:22.758 --> 00:40:24.160
AUDIENCE: With long waves.

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:27.360
AUDIENCE: It's using relatively
long wavelengths,

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:30.090
in the sort of hundreds of
megahertz wavelengths.

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:31.940
You can see the antenna
and all the wires

00:40:31.940 --> 00:40:33.090
for it on the left.

00:40:33.090 --> 00:40:34.710
And this is pretty much
state of the art when

00:40:34.710 --> 00:40:36.220
the Rad Lab is founded.

00:40:36.220 --> 00:40:38.530
And more or less, this
is an American radar.

00:40:38.530 --> 00:40:40.840
But the British have a version
of this that they used during

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:43.740
the Battle of Britain, they call
it Chain Home, that is

00:40:43.740 --> 00:40:45.880
able to detect attacking
aircraft.

00:40:45.880 --> 00:40:48.694
And it does actually
work in fact.

00:40:48.694 --> 00:40:52.680
In fact, the Pear Harbor attack
was detected by one of

00:40:52.680 --> 00:40:56.380
these right radars, as SCR-268
268, before it happened, a

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:57.670
couple hours before
it happened.

00:40:57.670 --> 00:41:00.480
But nobody really had any
faith in the technology.

00:41:00.480 --> 00:41:01.070
And it was new.

00:41:01.070 --> 00:41:02.350
And people didn't really
understand it.

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:04.220
And it was just a bunch of
blips on the screen.

00:41:04.220 --> 00:41:09.120
And the warning that the radar
station issued, was ignored.

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:11.970
Tells you something about any
technology needs to develop

00:41:11.970 --> 00:41:15.260
its own credibility and to have
people believe in it.

00:41:15.260 --> 00:41:19.100
After that, they tended to
believe in it, once it--

00:41:19.100 --> 00:41:20.920
But it's a very big radar.

00:41:20.920 --> 00:41:22.850
It's pretty unwieldy.

00:41:22.850 --> 00:41:24.710
You can see, it probably didn't
work very well in the

00:41:24.710 --> 00:41:28.720
rain, because the guys are all
standing there outside,

00:41:28.720 --> 00:41:31.740
exposed, and the electronics
are fairly exposed.

00:41:31.740 --> 00:41:34.800
He's just looking into an
oscilloscope right there.

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:36.760
That's a pre-World War
II oscilloscope.

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:38.685
It's the size of a Volkswagen
practically.

00:41:38.685 --> 00:41:43.610
And you see he's looking in
through just a darkened hood.

00:41:43.610 --> 00:41:45.840
And the British, the problem
was that for higher

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:48.750
frequencies, it was that very
hard to generate enough power,

00:41:48.750 --> 00:41:51.310
at what they call microwave
frequencies, which is sort of

00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:54.970
centimeters and below, in the
kind of high hundreds of

00:41:54.970 --> 00:41:57.870
megahertz up to several
gigahertz range.

00:41:57.870 --> 00:41:59.380
And the British come
up with this thing

00:41:59.380 --> 00:42:01.440
called a cavity magnetron.

00:42:06.390 --> 00:42:09.420
There it is.

00:42:09.420 --> 00:42:12.310
And again, it's not a
big device at all.

00:42:12.310 --> 00:42:17.080
But I'll show you the shape
of it in a little bit.

00:42:17.080 --> 00:42:20.200
It's got a central hole and
there's little resonators all

00:42:20.200 --> 00:42:21.720
around it, a very characteristic
shape of what's

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:22.610
inside there.

00:42:22.610 --> 00:42:24.780
You put that in a magnetic field
and pump a very high

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:27.960
voltage into it and it generates
really large, very

00:42:27.960 --> 00:42:29.990
high-power microwaves.

00:42:29.990 --> 00:42:33.040
And this has all kinds
of advantages.

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:35.760
But the key one is that it's
just small and the antennas

00:42:35.760 --> 00:42:38.250
are small and it allows you to
do all kinds of different

00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:39.110
things with it.

00:42:39.110 --> 00:42:42.720
But it implies a whole new
kind of electronics.

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:46.070
For example, you may be familiar
with this, but

00:42:46.070 --> 00:42:48.370
microwaves at high powers
don't really like to go

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:49.820
through wires.

00:42:49.820 --> 00:42:51.810
They need to go through pipes.

00:42:51.810 --> 00:42:52.670
What are those pipes called?

00:42:52.670 --> 00:42:54.090
Anybody know?

00:42:54.090 --> 00:42:54.560
AUDIENCE: Wave guides.

00:42:54.560 --> 00:42:55.730
PROFESSOR: They're called
wave guides, right.

00:42:55.730 --> 00:42:57.150
So you have to invent
a whole new kind

00:42:57.150 --> 00:42:58.440
of wiring or plumbing.

00:42:58.440 --> 00:43:01.750
You literally plumb this
kind of stuff through.

00:43:01.750 --> 00:43:04.220
And all that stuff
didn't exist.

00:43:04.220 --> 00:43:05.960
But what the British did
was they built this.

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:08.030
They figured out
that it worked.

00:43:08.030 --> 00:43:11.530
And in September of 1940, they
were being bombed to

00:43:11.530 --> 00:43:14.830
smithereens by the Nazis
on a regular basis.

00:43:14.830 --> 00:43:16.780
They were barely surviving
the war effort.

00:43:16.780 --> 00:43:18.920
And they didn't have a big
electronics industry.

00:43:18.920 --> 00:43:22.020
So it wasn't easy for them to
contemplate how to manufacture

00:43:22.020 --> 00:43:23.700
this thing in large numbers.

00:43:23.700 --> 00:43:28.380
So one scientist, his name was
Sir Henry Tizard, he came over

00:43:28.380 --> 00:43:32.140
to the US on an ocean liner,
exposed to Nazi submarines.

00:43:32.140 --> 00:43:33.630
And he brought one of these.

00:43:33.630 --> 00:43:37.630
Actually, I think he brought
three of them in a trunk that

00:43:37.630 --> 00:43:39.600
he kept under his bed
on the ocean liner.

00:43:39.600 --> 00:43:42.100
It was probably the most secret
military technology of

00:43:42.100 --> 00:43:44.000
the war at the time.

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:49.390
And he just brought it on this
civilian liner, sort of

00:43:49.390 --> 00:43:51.340
wrapped up in his socks
and underwear.

00:43:51.340 --> 00:43:52.280
That's exaggeration.

00:43:52.280 --> 00:43:54.510
I think he had a special
box for it.

00:43:54.510 --> 00:43:55.310
And he brought them.

00:43:55.310 --> 00:43:57.990
And he brought them to the
government and said, we have

00:43:57.990 --> 00:43:58.870
this thing.

00:43:58.870 --> 00:44:01.470
And we want you to have it.

00:44:01.470 --> 00:44:03.080
And we want the Americans
to figure it out.

00:44:03.080 --> 00:44:06.480
They actually intended for Bell
Labs to deal with it.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:09.160
And they brought it to the NDRC
and Bush sort of said,

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:10.470
well, we'll bring
this up to MIT.

00:44:10.470 --> 00:44:12.130
And they founded
a lab about it.

00:44:12.130 --> 00:44:15.230
That's what happens in
October of 1940.

00:44:15.230 --> 00:44:17.620
And that's when the Radiation
Lab is founded.

00:44:17.620 --> 00:44:19.760
And it's interesting, because
Rabi is said to

00:44:19.760 --> 00:44:20.970
have taken it out.

00:44:20.970 --> 00:44:23.570
And people said to him, he said
well, how does this thing

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:25.050
actually work?

00:44:25.050 --> 00:44:25.800
And they said well,
that's easy.

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:27.620
It works just like a whistle.

00:44:27.620 --> 00:44:31.040
It's like an electronic whistle,
because you put power

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:33.350
into it and it generates
a resonance.

00:44:33.350 --> 00:44:36.020
And then Rabi looks up at it and
he says, OK, well tell me

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:37.600
how a whistle works?

00:44:37.600 --> 00:44:39.625
And nobody at the time could
really explain to him how a

00:44:39.625 --> 00:44:41.120
whistle worked.

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:43.780
But that's not a bad way to
think about what the cavity

00:44:43.780 --> 00:44:46.530
magnetron does.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:48.860
AUDIENCE: So are you implying
that the establishment of the

00:44:48.860 --> 00:44:52.970
Rad Lab here really rested on
the proposition that it's not

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:54.980
what you know, but you know?

00:44:54.980 --> 00:44:56.370
PROFESSOR: To some degree.

00:44:56.370 --> 00:44:59.140
And actually it should be said
that of the three, I can't

00:44:59.140 --> 00:45:01.060
remember the exact number that
came over, one of them

00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:03.450
went to Bell Labs.

00:45:03.450 --> 00:45:06.130
And they also did a lot of work
in microwave radar during

00:45:06.130 --> 00:45:08.715
the war, but there was work
enough to do for everybody.

00:45:13.410 --> 00:45:14.720
So this is an image--

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:17.170
I actually have a blown-up
picture of this on the wall in

00:45:17.170 --> 00:45:20.110
my office, because one of the
great things about the Rad Lab

00:45:20.110 --> 00:45:24.590
is that photography was kind
of newly cheap at the time.

00:45:24.590 --> 00:45:27.890
And they documented a lot of
the research with thousands

00:45:27.890 --> 00:45:29.300
and thousands of photographs.

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:32.510
And years ago, I was working
through some of those

00:45:32.510 --> 00:45:36.020
photographs at the MIT Museum
and I said to Debbie Douglas,

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:38.576
there's great pictures of daily
life at MIT during World

00:45:38.576 --> 00:45:42.070
War II in the Rad Lab things,
that are not the sort of PR

00:45:42.070 --> 00:45:44.250
photos you usually see
about the Rad Lab.

00:45:44.250 --> 00:45:46.090
And then she took a bunch of
those photos, and they're all

00:45:46.090 --> 00:45:49.430
beautiful four by five
negatives, and blew them up

00:45:49.430 --> 00:45:52.610
and did a little art
show of them.

00:45:52.610 --> 00:45:54.510
And this is one which
I really like.

00:45:54.510 --> 00:45:56.480
And I'll turn the lights
off, if I can.

00:45:56.480 --> 00:45:58.600
Just generally you can
see them better.

00:46:12.460 --> 00:46:14.000
That do anything?

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:14.940
Nope.

00:46:14.940 --> 00:46:16.190
OK.

00:46:19.380 --> 00:46:24.490
Just to look at them a little
bit about life at MIT during

00:46:24.490 --> 00:46:26.630
the war, which Debbie's chapter
does a nice job of

00:46:26.630 --> 00:46:27.810
describing.

00:46:27.810 --> 00:46:29.590
What can you observe
from this image?

00:46:33.964 --> 00:46:34.936
Yep?

00:46:34.936 --> 00:46:37.970
AUDIENCE: The really, really
high waist lines.

00:46:37.970 --> 00:46:39.780
PROFESSOR: OK, high
waist lines.

00:46:39.780 --> 00:46:41.040
AUDIENCE: God, who wears there
pants up that high?

00:46:44.800 --> 00:46:45.750
AUDIENCE: Both women.

00:46:45.750 --> 00:46:47.390
PROFESSOR: There are
women there.

00:46:47.390 --> 00:46:50.500
A lot of women worked at the
Rad Lab, very, very mixed

00:46:50.500 --> 00:46:52.650
gender environment.

00:46:52.650 --> 00:46:54.620
AUDIENCE: That would be sort of
the scientific version of

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:57.190
Rosie the Riveter
in that sense.

00:46:57.190 --> 00:46:59.690
Lots of women go into the
workforce doing this--

00:46:59.690 --> 00:47:02.438
AUDIENCE: They were going to
work as scientists or as other

00:47:02.438 --> 00:47:02.900
technicians.

00:47:02.900 --> 00:47:04.540
PROFESSOR: Mostly as
technicians and

00:47:04.540 --> 00:47:06.190
administrators.

00:47:06.190 --> 00:47:08.810
Actually, I'm not even aware of
one that worked as a senior

00:47:08.810 --> 00:47:10.405
scientist or even an engineer.

00:47:13.260 --> 00:47:14.510
What else?

00:47:17.576 --> 00:47:19.052
AUDIENCE: The facilities
are not like--

00:47:22.004 --> 00:47:23.901
I can see piping.

00:47:23.901 --> 00:47:24.370
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:47:24.370 --> 00:47:26.020
So that's pretty much the
inside of Building 20.

00:47:26.020 --> 00:47:27.490
That's what it looked like.

00:47:27.490 --> 00:47:29.920
It was literally built
in a few weeks.

00:47:29.920 --> 00:47:31.170
What else?

00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:38.220
This one just captures this, I
think the sort of sense of the

00:47:38.220 --> 00:47:40.270
pace that the place
must have had.

00:47:40.270 --> 00:47:41.470
You have a sense, everybody's
busy.

00:47:41.470 --> 00:47:43.220
They're walking somewhere
quickly.

00:47:43.220 --> 00:47:44.290
They're moving things around.

00:47:44.290 --> 00:47:46.070
There's equipment coming
across the hall.

00:47:46.070 --> 00:47:47.680
That is a microwave
radar antenna.

00:47:47.680 --> 00:47:50.110
That's a pretty radical
departure from the previous

00:47:50.110 --> 00:47:52.570
slide I showed you of what a
radar antenna looked like.

00:47:52.570 --> 00:47:56.720
That you can imagine putting
on board an airplane.

00:47:56.720 --> 00:47:59.830
And there's also the two
cigarettes there.

00:47:59.830 --> 00:48:01.440
These guys all sort of
identically dressed.

00:48:01.440 --> 00:48:04.150
You get the sense it's a place
where just things are moving

00:48:04.150 --> 00:48:06.370
fast, sort of like MIT today.

00:48:06.370 --> 00:48:09.350
It wouldn't be out of place that
scene, in the Infinite

00:48:09.350 --> 00:48:11.620
Corridor between
classes today.

00:48:15.780 --> 00:48:20.340
Here is another image, a much
more formal one obviously, of

00:48:20.340 --> 00:48:23.630
the steering committee
of the Rad Lab.

00:48:23.630 --> 00:48:27.590
You see people in here, like I
mentioned Ivan Getting, who is

00:48:27.590 --> 00:48:34.700
here, who later went on, as I
mentioned, to sort of spun the

00:48:34.700 --> 00:48:36.780
GPS project.

00:48:36.780 --> 00:48:41.510
Anybody know who that
is right there?

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:44.070
That's Jerry Weisner, who
later became President

00:48:44.070 --> 00:48:47.540
Kennedy's science adviser
and president of MIT.

00:48:47.540 --> 00:48:50.930
I think this is Lee Dubridge,
who's the head of it.

00:48:50.930 --> 00:48:52.665
But again, a pretty informal
environment.

00:48:56.670 --> 00:49:00.110
Part of the weekly meeting,
another one.

00:49:00.110 --> 00:49:03.970
This may be the first time here,
and Debbie had mentioned

00:49:03.970 --> 00:49:06.080
in her article and a bunch you
mentioned in your response

00:49:06.080 --> 00:49:09.260
papers, the secrecy
that was going on.

00:49:09.260 --> 00:49:13.240
Now, these days if any of have
ever worked in even a mild

00:49:13.240 --> 00:49:15.320
corporate lab, you probably
have to wear a

00:49:15.320 --> 00:49:17.720
badge all the time.

00:49:17.720 --> 00:49:19.320
This was probably the first
time people had to

00:49:19.320 --> 00:49:20.960
wear badges at MIT.

00:49:20.960 --> 00:49:22.270
And this is what a badge
looked like.

00:49:22.270 --> 00:49:23.770
It was a little button.

00:49:23.770 --> 00:49:29.120
It had your picture on it,
your employee number, and

00:49:29.120 --> 00:49:31.430
allowed you to get into certain
places and not into

00:49:31.430 --> 00:49:34.050
other places.

00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:36.180
Again, it was called
the Radiation

00:49:36.180 --> 00:49:38.030
Laboratory for a reason.

00:49:38.030 --> 00:49:40.266
What was the reason?

00:49:40.266 --> 00:49:42.680
AUDIENCE: Disguise.

00:49:42.680 --> 00:49:44.850
PROFESSOR: To fool people into
thinking it might be a nuclear

00:49:44.850 --> 00:49:47.120
physics laboratory.

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:48.650
It was about radiation.

00:49:48.650 --> 00:49:52.510
But it was not called the
radar-- well, the word "radar"

00:49:52.510 --> 00:49:55.620
wasn't even well recognized
anyway at that point.

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:57.535
But it tried to disguise it.

00:50:00.250 --> 00:50:02.080
Again, as we mentioned,
lots of women

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:03.330
working in these labs.

00:50:08.290 --> 00:50:10.770
Probably a pretty different
work environment than what

00:50:10.770 --> 00:50:11.560
people were used to.

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:16.130
Even though we've talked about
women at MIT before, not in

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:18.240
these kind of numbers and
this much involved in

00:50:18.240 --> 00:50:19.490
the technical work.

00:50:22.650 --> 00:50:25.090
This is just a page out of the
yearbook that the Rad Lab

00:50:25.090 --> 00:50:26.720
produced, showing all
the different kinds

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:28.120
of things they did.

00:50:28.120 --> 00:50:30.280
It didn't come out that well
in the slide here.

00:50:33.450 --> 00:50:36.640
Another image, I love their
images of this sort of

00:50:36.640 --> 00:50:38.645
electronic experimentation
stuff.

00:50:42.080 --> 00:50:43.940
It has s sort of thrown
together sense of the

00:50:43.940 --> 00:50:47.100
director's chair,
an oscilloscope.

00:50:47.100 --> 00:50:49.110
What I find interesting is that
a lot of the connectors

00:50:49.110 --> 00:50:51.220
on all these machines are still
connectors you might use

00:50:51.220 --> 00:50:54.010
today, like a BMC connector.

00:50:54.010 --> 00:50:56.250
You still see those
everywhere.

00:50:56.250 --> 00:50:58.430
And this is what it took to get
this stuff up and running.

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:10.160
More pictures of the labs, in
this case without people.

00:51:10.160 --> 00:51:17.890
So this is probably the radar
that was shown before in that

00:51:17.890 --> 00:51:22.100
hallway photo and is one of the
more famous products of

00:51:22.100 --> 00:51:22.490
the Rad Lab.

00:51:22.490 --> 00:51:24.010
It was called H2X.

00:51:24.010 --> 00:51:26.810
And what H2X did was
it allowed, if

00:51:26.810 --> 00:51:28.720
you were in a bomber--

00:51:28.720 --> 00:51:32.160
the US and the British were
bombing Germany on a regular

00:51:32.160 --> 00:51:34.750
basis during most of the war--

00:51:34.750 --> 00:51:37.940
but they had this famous Norden
bombsight, which would

00:51:37.940 --> 00:51:39.570
allow you to sight bombs.

00:51:39.570 --> 00:51:41.060
What was the problem
with the Norden

00:51:41.060 --> 00:51:42.310
bombsight, anybody know?

00:51:46.514 --> 00:51:50.130
If it was cloudy, you
couldn't use it.

00:51:50.130 --> 00:51:52.790
And if anybody's ever been to
Germany or northern Europe,

00:51:52.790 --> 00:51:57.330
during eight months of the
year it's pretty cloudy.

00:51:57.330 --> 00:51:59.640
And what this is, is
a microwave radar.

00:51:59.640 --> 00:52:06.320
Again, it's not just an
advantage that the antenna is

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:08.230
small, but the wavelengths
are small enough.

00:52:08.230 --> 00:52:10.190
You can see things that are very
small, so you can make

00:52:10.190 --> 00:52:11.310
out a lot of detail.

00:52:11.310 --> 00:52:14.240
But you could actually fly over
in cloud cover and map

00:52:14.240 --> 00:52:16.890
out a river and a city
and all this stuff.

00:52:16.890 --> 00:52:23.150
And it allowed them to bomb with
radar, either at night or

00:52:23.150 --> 00:52:24.500
in bad weather.

00:52:24.500 --> 00:52:26.130
It had a huge impact.

00:52:26.130 --> 00:52:27.940
The other thing about H2X,
it was very important.

00:52:27.940 --> 00:52:29.940
It's worth keeping in mind about
radar, because you see

00:52:29.940 --> 00:52:31.590
this with other weapons
projects.

00:52:31.590 --> 00:52:34.590
Almost any weapons project that
got made during the war,

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:37.990
that actually was designed to
blow something up, it was

00:52:37.990 --> 00:52:42.600
very, very hard for it to have
impact in the war because for

00:52:42.600 --> 00:52:46.950
one thing, to go from a
prototype in October of 1940

00:52:46.950 --> 00:52:50.210
through development and testing
and production pretty

00:52:50.210 --> 00:52:51.790
much took the whole war.

00:52:51.790 --> 00:52:53.660
So there was basically one full

00:52:53.660 --> 00:52:55.080
product development cycle.

00:52:55.080 --> 00:52:57.590
If you look at like the great
airplanes of the Second World

00:52:57.590 --> 00:53:01.270
War, the B29, the B17, these
were all finished by the time

00:53:01.270 --> 00:53:04.170
the war started and it still
took them years to get into

00:53:04.170 --> 00:53:06.110
production.

00:53:06.110 --> 00:53:09.860
Whereas, if you had, a radar,
you could basically make one

00:53:09.860 --> 00:53:14.410
of them, send it out in the
field in one of a bombing raid

00:53:14.410 --> 00:53:16.770
of 1,000 bombers and
make a difference.

00:53:16.770 --> 00:53:20.410
So radar had this leveraging
effect, where you could use

00:53:20.410 --> 00:53:21.980
very, very small numbers
of them and

00:53:21.980 --> 00:53:23.750
still have a big impact.

00:53:23.750 --> 00:53:27.750
Which any kind of gun, if you
didn't make a gun in numbers

00:53:27.750 --> 00:53:29.730
of the tens of thousands, it
was not going to have any

00:53:29.730 --> 00:53:30.980
impact on the war.

00:53:34.888 --> 00:53:35.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:35.800 --> 00:53:37.734
PROFESSOR: Yep.

00:53:37.734 --> 00:53:41.220
AUDIENCE: How long between the
development of that product

00:53:41.220 --> 00:53:44.720
would it be then on plane?

00:53:44.720 --> 00:53:46.210
PROFESSOR: In the case of the
radiation lab, it would be

00:53:46.210 --> 00:53:46.955
weeks or months.

00:53:46.955 --> 00:53:47.670
AUDIENCE: Weeks or months.

00:53:47.670 --> 00:53:51.200
PROFESSOR: And actually, no
small number of MIT engineers

00:53:51.200 --> 00:53:53.170
went in the field,
made them work,

00:53:53.170 --> 00:53:55.100
went on bombing missions.

00:53:55.100 --> 00:53:58.700
A few of them were killed,
literally taking these things

00:53:58.700 --> 00:54:00.570
in the field.

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:03.520
Think about it any lab prototype
you've ever made, it

00:54:03.520 --> 00:54:06.770
may be a little rickety in terms
of its robustness for

00:54:06.770 --> 00:54:07.580
being in the field.

00:54:07.580 --> 00:54:10.340
It takes a lot of engineering to
go from there to a package

00:54:10.340 --> 00:54:12.480
that some soldier is going
to take out of a box.

00:54:12.480 --> 00:54:13.950
They didn't always wait
for that time.

00:54:13.950 --> 00:54:16.610
And they did send people
directly from the Rad Lab into

00:54:16.610 --> 00:54:19.490
the field, to train the troops
and help them get up to speed.

00:54:19.490 --> 00:54:23.260
In fact, Karl Compton, the
president of MIT, was not--

00:54:23.260 --> 00:54:26.780
in a sense, Bush, before then,
he was junior to Compton.

00:54:26.780 --> 00:54:30.020
He goes in and becomes head of
the NDRC and is senior to him.

00:54:30.020 --> 00:54:32.400
Compton became head of what was
called the Office of Field

00:54:32.400 --> 00:54:34.250
Service, where they
did exactly that.

00:54:34.250 --> 00:54:36.490
They took all these things out
and they helped people

00:54:36.490 --> 00:54:39.100
understand how to use them.

00:54:39.100 --> 00:54:42.780
There's a B17 at Hanscom
Field, right out in the

00:54:42.780 --> 00:54:48.920
suburbs here, where the
Rad Lab had a station.

00:54:48.920 --> 00:54:52.560
And they would do a lot of
testing and a lot of different

00:54:52.560 --> 00:54:54.910
experimentation and flight
tests and stuff,

00:54:54.910 --> 00:54:57.380
also at Logan Airport.

00:54:57.380 --> 00:55:05.480
Here's a H2X installation inside
a B17, to allow the

00:55:05.480 --> 00:55:07.320
radar operator to look
through the sight.

00:55:07.320 --> 00:55:09.130
And again, think about
what a different kind

00:55:09.130 --> 00:55:10.600
of radar this is.

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:13.970
The one I showed you from
before, the prewar radar,

00:55:13.970 --> 00:55:16.150
they're basically soldiers on
the battlefield, these guys.

00:55:16.150 --> 00:55:19.170
They're wearing helmets and
they're very exposed.

00:55:19.170 --> 00:55:22.180
Here, not only are you in a
high-altitude bomber, but the

00:55:22.180 --> 00:55:23.010
guy has a desk.

00:55:23.010 --> 00:55:26.940
It's much more like bringing a
laboratory out into the war

00:55:26.940 --> 00:55:27.970
time field.

00:55:27.970 --> 00:55:31.340
And there's a lot of interesting
stuff about

00:55:31.340 --> 00:55:34.410
thinking about radar as a way
to isolate yourself from the

00:55:34.410 --> 00:55:36.645
battlefield and manipulate
things on screens.

00:55:39.170 --> 00:55:41.480
One of the technicians who
worked on these radars was a

00:55:41.480 --> 00:55:43.080
guy named--

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:45.430
well, what's the name--

00:55:45.430 --> 00:55:47.290
Douglas Engelbart.

00:55:47.290 --> 00:55:48.540
Anybody know what he did?

00:55:51.170 --> 00:55:54.180
He invented the mouse.

00:55:54.180 --> 00:55:57.240
And he'll tell you, during the
war I worked on radar.

00:55:57.240 --> 00:55:59.930
And I started to deal with like
moving things around as

00:55:59.930 --> 00:56:02.870
blips on screens using things
to turn things around.

00:56:02.870 --> 00:56:04.940
And after the war, when I
started to work at Stanford

00:56:04.940 --> 00:56:09.680
and user interface stuff, he
was not an MIT guy, some of

00:56:09.680 --> 00:56:12.540
the ideas for interactive
computing really came out of

00:56:12.540 --> 00:56:15.830
this idea of looking
at a screen.

00:56:18.630 --> 00:56:22.440
This is a famous image,
one of the Rad Lab's

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:24.400
sort of iconic images.

00:56:24.400 --> 00:56:25.906
Anybody know what it is?

00:56:25.906 --> 00:56:26.860
AUDIENCE: It's Cape Cod.

00:56:26.860 --> 00:56:27.930
PROFESSOR: It's Cape
Cod, right.

00:56:27.930 --> 00:56:30.430
So this here is just a
map showing you where

00:56:30.430 --> 00:56:31.650
the airplane was.

00:56:31.650 --> 00:56:32.760
And there's a radar on there.

00:56:32.760 --> 00:56:34.670
The antenna spins around.

00:56:34.670 --> 00:56:39.870
And this is one of the first H2X
images, plotting out the

00:56:39.870 --> 00:56:42.870
contours of the land there.

00:56:42.870 --> 00:56:46.570
And so you'll see this appear in
another second in something

00:56:46.570 --> 00:56:48.260
I'll show you.

00:56:48.260 --> 00:56:51.180
But this gives you the sense of,
very, very different from

00:56:51.180 --> 00:56:52.150
blips on a screen.

00:56:52.150 --> 00:56:54.860
You're really able to sort
of map where you.

00:56:54.860 --> 00:56:57.740
A whole other level of detail
and in the military setting,

00:56:57.740 --> 00:57:00.630
that was very, very important.

00:57:00.630 --> 00:57:03.090
Here's even a higher
resolution one.

00:57:03.090 --> 00:57:06.360
This is an image from an
airplane, looking at another

00:57:06.360 --> 00:57:08.380
airplane nearby.

00:57:08.380 --> 00:57:11.265
And just to get a sense for
that resolution, too.

00:57:11.265 --> 00:57:13.840
You know, crude by today's
standards in some sense of

00:57:13.840 --> 00:57:20.510
digital radars and stuff, but
pretty fancy for that day.

00:57:20.510 --> 00:57:26.570
And anybody know what this
is, dead giveaway?

00:57:26.570 --> 00:57:28.780
This is the northern coast
of France on D-Day.

00:57:28.780 --> 00:57:33.770
And here is the radar image of
the fleet that's going to be

00:57:33.770 --> 00:57:36.140
the invasion force, taken
from an airplane.

00:57:36.140 --> 00:57:43.030
And you can see 6 June, 7:00
o'clock in the morning, taken

00:57:43.030 --> 00:57:44.160
from a plane that was above.

00:57:44.160 --> 00:57:46.530
This is Western England.

00:57:50.100 --> 00:57:52.760
Another interesting
radar is this one.

00:57:52.760 --> 00:57:55.540
It's a SCR-584.

00:57:55.540 --> 00:57:57.460
It was actually the first
tracking radar.

00:57:57.460 --> 00:58:00.310
And so in the history of control
theory and feedback

00:58:00.310 --> 00:58:02.200
control, it was the first radar
that could actually move

00:58:02.200 --> 00:58:05.020
its antenna based on
where it's target

00:58:05.020 --> 00:58:07.500
was and follow something.

00:58:07.500 --> 00:58:13.840
And they actually used these to
track the buzz bombs that

00:58:13.840 --> 00:58:17.050
came across to England
later in the war

00:58:17.050 --> 00:58:18.580
and shoot them down.

00:58:18.580 --> 00:58:23.710
It became also sort of an iconic
radar, because this

00:58:23.710 --> 00:58:24.940
tracking head, it's
interesting,

00:58:24.940 --> 00:58:26.485
it was made by Chrysler.

00:58:26.485 --> 00:58:28.400
And a lot of the gearing
in it was taken

00:58:28.400 --> 00:58:30.650
out of Chrysler trucks.

00:58:30.650 --> 00:58:31.680
And it has these servos on it.

00:58:31.680 --> 00:58:35.120
It was a very, very good, very
high precision tracking head.

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:37.970
You see it in post-war
photographs for tracking

00:58:37.970 --> 00:58:40.980
rockets and doing sort
of early NASA work.

00:58:40.980 --> 00:58:44.330
And you'll still see
these radar mounts.

00:58:44.330 --> 00:58:46.690
If you ever watch like storm
trackers or anything, and

00:58:46.690 --> 00:58:49.510
their people who track tornadoes
and stuff, they

00:58:49.510 --> 00:58:53.250
actually use army surplus
radar mounts like this.

00:58:53.250 --> 00:58:56.930
But this radar also, sort of
serves the same purpose as the

00:58:56.930 --> 00:58:59.040
268 that I showed you before.

00:58:59.040 --> 00:59:02.530
but again, they bring the
operators inside the trailer,

00:59:02.530 --> 00:59:04.500
inside this sort of
closed laboratory.

00:59:04.500 --> 00:59:07.760
And it's very much thinking
of the battlefield and the

00:59:07.760 --> 00:59:10.680
electronic battlefield of
bringing all these blips into

00:59:10.680 --> 00:59:12.620
a laboratory setting.

00:59:12.620 --> 00:59:16.250
And again, but the ultimate
culmination of that are these

00:59:16.250 --> 00:59:18.280
big command and control centers
you see during the

00:59:18.280 --> 00:59:21.570
Cold War, you see during the
space program, but it's just

00:59:21.570 --> 00:59:24.040
the beginning of that.

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:27.420
That's the inside of a CR-584,
where they can plot

00:59:27.420 --> 00:59:29.370
things on the map.

00:59:29.370 --> 00:59:31.010
Also, this was one
of the early air

00:59:31.010 --> 00:59:32.950
traffic control radars.

00:59:32.950 --> 00:59:35.600
It was precise enough that they
could tell the pilots

00:59:35.600 --> 00:59:39.350
where they were and guide them
by radio, say come up, come

00:59:39.350 --> 00:59:43.030
down, come up and down, and land
them in very, very rough

00:59:43.030 --> 00:59:44.280
weather conditions.

00:59:47.600 --> 00:59:49.470
So I think this is
the last image.

00:59:49.470 --> 00:59:54.210
This is actually an
important image.

00:59:54.210 --> 00:59:57.370
At the end of the war, anybody
know what happened to the

00:59:57.370 --> 00:59:58.620
Radiation Lab?

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:03.470
Is it here today?

01:00:03.470 --> 01:00:05.270
Any of you students
in the Rad Lab?

01:00:05.270 --> 01:00:07.331
Nope.

01:00:07.331 --> 01:00:10.140
AUDIENCE: I think part
of it became the RLE.

01:00:10.140 --> 01:00:12.730
PROFESSOR: Part of it
did become the RLE.

01:00:12.730 --> 01:00:14.810
And the rest of it?

01:00:14.810 --> 01:00:16.830
It just closed down one day.

01:00:16.830 --> 01:00:24.220
And went from 1945 to 1946, it
shut down by a factor of 95%,

01:00:24.220 --> 01:00:28.400
and then all together in 1947.

01:00:28.400 --> 01:00:29.720
Which is a very interesting
thing.

01:00:29.720 --> 01:00:31.850
It would be very hard to
do in today's world.

01:00:31.850 --> 01:00:35.750
Remember from the Hunter Dupree
article about Bush, one

01:00:35.750 --> 01:00:38.380
of the reasons he was able to
grow this thing so quickly and

01:00:38.380 --> 01:00:41.160
so rapidly was that he always
promised it would only last

01:00:41.160 --> 01:00:42.580
until the war was over.

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:44.630
And then it ended and he
kept true to his word.

01:00:44.630 --> 01:00:46.630
And the OSRD closed down.

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:49.590
The NDRC closed down.

01:00:49.590 --> 01:00:53.820
And the Rad Lab just
closed down.

01:00:53.820 --> 01:00:58.600
Which by the way, was not a
bad way to influence the

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:00.090
American electronics industry.

01:01:00.090 --> 01:01:02.855
Why?

01:01:02.855 --> 01:01:04.707
AUDIENCE: Probably there were
lots of people who knew about

01:01:04.707 --> 01:01:06.100
electronics looking for work.

01:01:06.100 --> 01:01:08.050
PROFESSOR: It dispersed
all that knowledge

01:01:08.050 --> 01:01:09.710
out into the world.

01:01:09.710 --> 01:01:12.980
And a lot of those people, many
of them went to work on

01:01:12.980 --> 01:01:15.470
radar, but a lot of them went
to work on television.

01:01:15.470 --> 01:01:18.800
The early American television
industry was largely composed

01:01:18.800 --> 01:01:21.760
of Rad Lab graduates,
who knew a lot about

01:01:21.760 --> 01:01:23.770
high frequency control.

01:01:23.770 --> 01:01:27.690
Also a lot of the early vacuum
but computers, Eckert and

01:01:27.690 --> 01:01:32.210
Mauchly, who built ENIAC at
University of Pennsylvania--

01:01:32.210 --> 01:01:33.250
I know I'm going to
forget which one--

01:01:33.250 --> 01:01:35.610
I think it was Mauchly, came
from the Rad Lab, where he

01:01:35.610 --> 01:01:38.580
learned about how to make vacuum
tubes do high-speed

01:01:38.580 --> 01:01:41.740
pulse electronics, which by the
way is essentially digital

01:01:41.740 --> 01:01:43.780
electronics.

01:01:43.780 --> 01:01:46.140
So these people all dispersed
into the world.

01:01:46.140 --> 01:01:49.510
The RLE, which still does exist
today, became the kind

01:01:49.510 --> 01:01:55.150
of intellectual core, people
like Wiesner and Wiener, a

01:01:55.150 --> 01:01:55.980
bunch of other people--

01:01:55.980 --> 01:02:00.550
I'll talk about that in the
next two weeks, I think.

01:02:00.550 --> 01:02:02.910
And otherwise, the Radiation
Lab closed down.

01:02:02.910 --> 01:02:06.440
But before they did, I meant
to bring one of these, they

01:02:06.440 --> 01:02:10.310
published everything they did in
a big series of textbooks.

01:02:10.310 --> 01:02:13.250
I think it's like
28 textbooks.

01:02:13.250 --> 01:02:16.240
And they just published it out
to the world by McGraw Hill,

01:02:16.240 --> 01:02:19.350
not secret, not classified,
none of that.

01:02:19.350 --> 01:02:23.780
And some of the first books in
servomechanisms were there,

01:02:23.780 --> 01:02:25.700
antenna design, systems
engineering.

01:02:25.700 --> 01:02:27.780
The first book ever in systems
engineering came

01:02:27.780 --> 01:02:28.570
out of the Rad Lab.

01:02:28.570 --> 01:02:30.860
It was called Radar System
Engineering.

01:02:30.860 --> 01:02:32.730
And they have this
characteristic.

01:02:32.730 --> 01:02:34.290
You can still get them.

01:02:34.290 --> 01:02:36.000
But the original ones
had this sort of

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:37.540
burgundy cover with it.

01:02:37.540 --> 01:02:39.410
And this was the logo they
had on the front.

01:02:39.410 --> 01:02:40.660
So what is that logo?

01:02:44.160 --> 01:02:45.880
It's the Cape Cod image.

01:02:45.880 --> 01:02:48.180
Anybody know what this is?

01:02:48.180 --> 01:02:49.120
AUDIENCE: That's the cavity.

01:02:49.120 --> 01:02:49.360
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:02:49.360 --> 01:02:52.710
That's the shape inside
the cavity magnetron.

01:02:52.710 --> 01:02:54.990
It's sort of their logo.

01:02:54.990 --> 01:02:57.410
And if you cut a cavity
magnetron open, that's what

01:02:57.410 --> 01:03:00.320
you'd see, is those little
circles that are all the

01:03:00.320 --> 01:03:03.900
different resonate cavities,
where I believe the wavelength

01:03:03.900 --> 01:03:06.785
of the radar is the
circumference of that cavity.

01:03:10.530 --> 01:03:11.360
I meant to bring--

01:03:11.360 --> 01:03:13.570
I have a few of the volumes.

01:03:13.570 --> 01:03:14.680
I don't have the whole set.

01:03:14.680 --> 01:03:15.730
You can buy the whole
set on eBay.

01:03:15.730 --> 01:03:16.685
It's not hard to fine.

01:03:16.685 --> 01:03:19.070
Because most people think
of it as obsolete.

01:03:19.070 --> 01:03:23.590
But you can find them in
the libraries, as well.

01:03:23.590 --> 01:03:25.660
And it's a very famous
textbook series.

01:03:25.660 --> 01:03:28.440
And for most people who studied
electronics in the

01:03:28.440 --> 01:03:32.100
postwar period, they learned a
lot of it from this Radiation

01:03:32.100 --> 01:03:33.810
Lab series of textbooks.

01:03:33.810 --> 01:03:36.400
So we were talking about secrecy
and the effects of

01:03:36.400 --> 01:03:38.280
secrecy on campus.

01:03:38.280 --> 01:03:41.460
This is a sort of anti-secrecy
effect, that it really just

01:03:41.460 --> 01:03:42.990
had the goal of--

01:03:42.990 --> 01:03:44.630
yes, the Russians got it.

01:03:44.630 --> 01:03:46.310
Yes.

01:03:46.310 --> 01:03:48.280
Maybe some of our enemies
learned something from it.

01:03:48.280 --> 01:03:52.930
But that was probably way less
proportional than what our own

01:03:52.930 --> 01:03:55.726
people learn about it and
what came out of it.

01:03:55.726 --> 01:03:59.480
I think that's my last slide.

01:03:59.480 --> 01:04:01.970
AUDIENCE: That was the origins
of OpenCourseWare?

01:04:01.970 --> 01:04:03.250
PROFESSOR: The origins
of OpenCourseWare,

01:04:03.250 --> 01:04:04.140
in some way, yeah.

01:04:04.140 --> 01:04:06.010
I mean I think that was the
same kind of spirit.

01:04:06.010 --> 01:04:08.170
And that's one of the reasons
that people like Bush felt

01:04:08.170 --> 01:04:10.190
that this stuff belong
in universities.

01:04:10.190 --> 01:04:13.220
Because if it was in the Navy
lab or in an Army lab, it

01:04:13.220 --> 01:04:15.110
would go behind closed
doors and stay there

01:04:15.110 --> 01:04:15.880
forever pretty much.

01:04:15.880 --> 01:04:17.670
It's very hard to get stuff
published out of there.

01:04:23.530 --> 01:04:25.840
I'll just look at in
the numbers I have

01:04:25.840 --> 01:04:27.090
here, if any of them--

01:04:30.930 --> 01:04:35.580
So then going on from there,
I mean the Research Lab of

01:04:35.580 --> 01:04:38.050
Electronics is a really
interesting

01:04:38.050 --> 01:04:39.240
topic in and of itself.

01:04:39.240 --> 01:04:43.670
And they get into acoustics
in a big way.

01:04:43.670 --> 01:04:47.330
People like, as we mentioned,
Jerry Wiesner is there.

01:04:47.330 --> 01:04:49.100
Weiner is there.

01:04:49.100 --> 01:04:50.980
People like Amar Bose
come out of there.

01:04:50.980 --> 01:04:53.310
And the Bose Corporation, who
may make your headphones or

01:04:53.310 --> 01:04:56.900
your speakers, is a spin-off
from the RLE.

01:04:56.900 --> 01:04:59.460
Even people like Noam Chomsky
kind of get their start in

01:04:59.460 --> 01:05:00.000
that world.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:04.520
And there are a lot of
intellectual ties to, this is

01:05:04.520 --> 01:05:07.630
a little bit of a diversion, but
if you think about some of

01:05:07.630 --> 01:05:10.780
the early work that goes on in
linguistics here that Chomsky

01:05:10.780 --> 01:05:13.650
does, it has very much the
same kind of systems

01:05:13.650 --> 01:05:18.290
engineering approach to it,
about thinking about grammar

01:05:18.290 --> 01:05:21.290
and language, along the lines
of people are thinking about

01:05:21.290 --> 01:05:24.830
these different kinds of systems
and systems ideas.

01:05:24.830 --> 01:05:27.210
That was the Lily Kay piece that
Will mentioned, that we

01:05:27.210 --> 01:05:28.540
cut off the syllabus
for this year.

01:05:28.540 --> 01:05:31.300
The same thing in biology,
people thinking about

01:05:31.300 --> 01:05:33.830
information and communication
in these more and

01:05:33.830 --> 01:05:35.510
more unified ways.

01:05:35.510 --> 01:05:39.110
So what's remarkable about the
war is that this effort ended

01:05:39.110 --> 01:05:41.810
at the end of the Second World
War, but it had all of these

01:05:41.810 --> 01:05:43.740
kind of fingers that lasted.

01:05:43.740 --> 01:05:47.730
We'll talk next week about
Whirlwind and digital

01:05:47.730 --> 01:05:52.230
computing and aerospace
and stuff on campus.

01:05:52.230 --> 01:05:55.510
But it's not a coincidence the
way that Cybernetics is

01:05:55.510 --> 01:05:58.750
published in 1948, Claude
Shannon's information theory

01:05:58.750 --> 01:06:02.260
is published in 1948.

01:06:02.260 --> 01:06:06.550
Also interestingly, I think it's
1948, Kurt Vonnegut first

01:06:06.550 --> 01:06:10.230
novel, Player Piano, is
published in 1948.

01:06:10.230 --> 01:06:12.670
Has anybody read that book?

01:06:12.670 --> 01:06:13.870
It's a really interesting
book.

01:06:13.870 --> 01:06:19.400
And the lead character in it,
I believe is named Norbert.

01:06:19.400 --> 01:06:20.290
Am I right about that?

01:06:20.290 --> 01:06:21.270
It's been a while.

01:06:21.270 --> 01:06:23.470
It's got a very clear allusion
to Norbert Wiener.

01:06:23.470 --> 01:06:25.980
It's all about the implications
of cybernetics in

01:06:25.980 --> 01:06:29.960
factories and other
kinds of settings.

01:06:29.960 --> 01:06:33.220
And there is this intellectual
thread that runs through a lot

01:06:33.220 --> 01:06:37.570
of this work about this link
between systems, and human

01:06:37.570 --> 01:06:41.900
machine interfaces, and
communication, and feedback

01:06:41.900 --> 01:06:44.720
control, and computing,
that you can carry

01:06:44.720 --> 01:06:45.710
that through at MIT.

01:06:45.710 --> 01:06:47.430
And we'll talk later
about Project MAC,

01:06:47.430 --> 01:06:49.420
which is the 1960s.

01:06:49.420 --> 01:06:53.450
20 years later, people are
still thinking about

01:06:53.450 --> 01:06:55.800
interactive computing in
very similar ways.

01:06:55.800 --> 01:07:00.010
I mentioned Doug Engelbart, who
was not an MIT guy, but

01:07:00.010 --> 01:07:03.370
very much is very clear in his
memoirs, that he started

01:07:03.370 --> 01:07:05.380
thinking about these issues when
he was interacting with

01:07:05.380 --> 01:07:07.410
the radar during the war.

01:07:07.410 --> 01:07:11.180
And then it's only out of this
that you really get the

01:07:11.180 --> 01:07:15.620
beginnings of digital computing
and I think, and

01:07:15.620 --> 01:07:18.910
I'll talk about this next time,
a very particularly MIT

01:07:18.910 --> 01:07:22.600
take on those technologies
that's not so much focused on

01:07:22.600 --> 01:07:25.710
the kind of basic mathematics
of them, but really thinking

01:07:25.710 --> 01:07:28.850
of these computers as embedded
in control systems, much in

01:07:28.850 --> 01:07:30.830
the way that all these different
radars were embedded

01:07:30.830 --> 01:07:31.680
in control systems.

01:07:31.680 --> 01:07:35.000
So that's where you can sort of
see that the way that MIT

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:38.030
is organized, the way that the
federal government is funding

01:07:38.030 --> 01:07:40.920
science and technology, and
the politics of Washington

01:07:40.920 --> 01:07:43.720
around it, and the actual
content of what kind of work

01:07:43.720 --> 01:07:46.480
people are doing, and what sort
of ideas they're doing,

01:07:46.480 --> 01:07:49.350
are all really very much
connected in this story about

01:07:49.350 --> 01:07:50.220
World War II.

01:07:50.220 --> 01:07:55.190
It's hard to overemphasize how
much profound influence on the

01:07:55.190 --> 01:07:58.110
world that we live in, even just
even just the local world

01:07:58.110 --> 01:08:02.000
here, came out of this really
just five-year, seven-year

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:04.790
period at MIT.

01:08:04.790 --> 01:08:08.690
We also looked at "Science,
The Endless Frontier." And

01:08:08.690 --> 01:08:12.560
that was where Truman came to
Bush at the end of the war,

01:08:12.560 --> 01:08:14.550
pretty much at the end of the
war, because Truman isn't even

01:08:14.550 --> 01:08:17.540
president until right before the
war ends, and says, what

01:08:17.540 --> 01:08:18.920
are we going to do in
this in the future?

01:08:18.920 --> 01:08:20.670
How are we going to
take this forward?

01:08:20.670 --> 01:08:24.109
And Bush writes this report,
whereas somebody commented in

01:08:24.109 --> 01:08:26.450
the response for today, it's
really very forward thinking

01:08:26.450 --> 01:08:28.800
where he says, OK, we're
done with war.

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:29.630
That's important.

01:08:29.630 --> 01:08:32.810
But let's really think about
doing this in a context that's

01:08:32.810 --> 01:08:35.740
really going to help our people,
and that's medicine

01:08:35.740 --> 01:08:40.830
and biomed and other sorts of
civilian applications to it.

01:08:40.830 --> 01:08:45.069
And that report to this day,
I mean that's sort of--

01:08:45.069 --> 01:08:49.090
has anybody read that before the
class or heard about it?

01:08:49.090 --> 01:08:51.640
It's sort of basic required
reading, if you have a career

01:08:51.640 --> 01:08:52.620
in science in the US.

01:08:52.620 --> 01:08:56.330
It really is considered the
template for how the NIH and

01:08:56.330 --> 01:09:00.229
the NSF and a lot of other
federal agencies work.

01:09:00.229 --> 01:09:03.350
Interestingly, it's not so much
the continuation of the

01:09:03.350 --> 01:09:05.359
OSRD model.

01:09:05.359 --> 01:09:09.300
The OSRD model kind
of dies in 1945.

01:09:09.300 --> 01:09:11.700
If anything, it's carried on
by the Office of Naval

01:09:11.700 --> 01:09:14.919
Research, which is a very small
office, during the five

01:09:14.919 --> 01:09:16.890
years after the war.

01:09:16.890 --> 01:09:19.750
And then late in the '50s, I
think it's picked up again

01:09:19.750 --> 01:09:22.840
when DARPA is formed in
1958, also with a

01:09:22.840 --> 01:09:24.130
very big MIT input.

01:09:24.130 --> 01:09:26.470
We'll talk about
that next time.

01:09:26.470 --> 01:09:30.490
But if you want to look at the
modern heir to the OSRD, it's

01:09:30.490 --> 01:09:31.729
not the National Science
Foundation.

01:09:31.729 --> 01:09:32.990
The National Science Foundation

01:09:32.990 --> 01:09:34.649
works by peer review.

01:09:34.649 --> 01:09:37.529
It has a charge to not only fund
the best science, but to

01:09:37.529 --> 01:09:41.319
do education and to sort of
spread its resources out,

01:09:41.319 --> 01:09:44.910
throughout the country in
a kind of even way.

01:09:44.910 --> 01:09:47.870
Whereas DARPA is much more
based on the model of the

01:09:47.870 --> 01:09:50.510
OSRD, intentionally or
unintentionally.

01:09:50.510 --> 01:09:54.010
You have very strong program
managers, who can sort of

01:09:54.010 --> 01:09:56.700
shape the fields the
way they see fit.

01:09:56.700 --> 01:09:59.800
It's within the military, but
it doesn't belong to the Air

01:09:59.800 --> 01:10:01.370
Force or the Army or the Navy.

01:10:01.370 --> 01:10:03.110
And it has does its
own sort of thing.

01:10:03.110 --> 01:10:05.480
And it's sort of set apart,
very much in the same way.

01:10:05.480 --> 01:10:06.210
But that's--

01:10:06.210 --> 01:10:07.230
AUDIENCE: It's run academics.

01:10:07.230 --> 01:10:07.990
PROFESSOR: --another story.

01:10:07.990 --> 01:10:10.450
It's run by academics, yeah.

01:10:10.450 --> 01:10:13.680
And the first director was
Jack Ruina, who was a

01:10:13.680 --> 01:10:15.380
colleague of ours here.

01:10:15.380 --> 01:10:16.590
We'll talk about
that next time.

01:10:16.590 --> 01:10:17.830
That's a post-Sputnik thing.

01:10:17.830 --> 01:10:19.790
That's the next big thing
that happened.

